      "name": "",
      "username": "Alex",
      "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.trainerday.com/alex/{size}/1331_2.png",
      "created_at": "2022-08-03T05:19:35.430Z",
      "cooked": "<p>In general I ride my CX bike on trails mostly and when it comes to technical/steep hills I can\u2019t make it to the top I am pretty sure the power meter helped me dial in my power so I had reserves to get through the steepest parts but I am not sure on that <img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/images/emoji/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"></p>\n<p>My guess is you would be so addicted to seeing and understanding your power you would be forced to buy a bike computer too. So this might be another reason not to get one <img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/images/emoji/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"></p>\n<p>The numbers are surprising. Going over FTP on your MTB (any bike on hills) is incredibly easy so knowing your are depleting your reserves can help you back off.</p>",
